<TEXT>
the federal government will pay nearly 25 
million to counties hit by the 1989 loma prieta earthquake to help 
displaced poor people officials said thursday 
federal emergency management agency officials backed out of a 
similar agreement announced in february saying it had been signed 
under a misunderstanding 
legal aid lawyers for the poor said the new settlement had been 
approved by fema highlevel justice department officials and us 
district judge eugene lynch 
assistant us attorney george stoll confirmed the agreement was 
reached saying it was binding and the government should provide 
funding quickly 
we are confident they will not renege said morgan gilhuly 
a volunteer san francisco lawyer this is a good deal for fema 
and a good deal for people who lost their housing 
under the settlement fema is to distribute the funds to san 
francisco santa cruz and alameda counties said stepehn ronfeldt 
of legal aid society of alameda county 
the funds will be distributed according to each countys 
proportionate losses in lowincome housing units 
san francisco planning official carla javits said the city would 
use most of its money to renovate two centers providing 425 beds 
and a variety of services to the homeless 
alameda county which lost more than 1100 residential hotel 
rooms will use some money for reconstruction and some for a newly 
designed housing voucher program said rae mary of the countys 
office of community development santa cruz county has similar 
plans ronfeldt said 
</TEXT>
