<TEXT>
computers are challenging the sandbox and 
easel in preschool programs across the country although educators 
have mixed opinions about introducing technology to toddlers 
youngsters should begin as early as possible to view computers 
as a tool said suzanne thouvenelle vice president of an 
alexandria va firm that developed software for young children 
but john lindley principal of south colby elementary school in 
port orchard wash countered children need to be involved in 
active learning computers are too passive computer introduction 
to them is something they get too much of already and thats 
television 
even bernard gifford vice president of education marketing for 
apple computer inc acknowledged that computers in preschool may 
be a bit too early 
i believe strongly in making it available to kids but i would 
be reluctant to impose a structured program at that age i think 
the most important skills for youngsters at ages 3 and 4 frankly 
are social skills 
in a sampling of head start preschool classes around the 
country children used computers to create animals and plant 
imaginary gardens one program allowed them to combine facial 
features on the computer while dictating stories to their teachers 
the youngsters were so excited and motivated by the computers 
that attendance improved thouvenelle said parents also showed a 
greater interest in their childrens work and enthusiastically 
volunteered to work in the classroom 
walt disney computer software inc recently introduced a line 
of software that had been tested at two burbank calif 
preschools nowhere on the package does it say educational 
software notes sam palahnuk walt disney product developer 
what we claim this stuff is a fun exploratory software for your 
kid 
fun is what 3yearold heather leffler 4yearold emily koleini 
and her 2yearold brother massoud were having during a 
demonstration of the software at an upscale virginia mall with 
parents nearby the children watched in delight the colorful 
animated graphics of mickey mouse and his friends and listened to 
the digitalized speech fully orchestrated music and reallife 
sound effects 
the youngsters used numbers to help mickey mouse plan a birthday 
party forggoofy named animals at a county fair with letters of the 
alphabet and identified shapes as mickey performed magic acts 
it certainly isnt boring said andrea fleury of mclean 
va as she threatened to leave her 3yearold who had tinkered 
with the computer for nearly two hours 
we went for the approach let kids really have fun and theyll 
learn as a side effect said palahnuk we dont want to claim 
that its going to teach your kid anything we think it will but 
you start getting into teaching philosophy and curriculum and all 
that kind of thing 
a study by the national association of elementary school 
principals found that elementary school children are more likely to 
use computers in school than high school or college students and 
even 15 percent of kindergartners and preschoolers in the public 
schools use computers 
research dating back to 1932 showed that technology as simple 
as a typewriter had significant effects on the reading and writing 
performance of elementary students said james e dezel 
international business machines corp vice president the 
technology available to schools today and in the future could bring 
about amazing results 
ibm sponsored the threeyear study exploring classroom uses of 
computers with children and parents in head start a popular 
federal preschool program that provides education meals and health 
screening for poor youngsters aged 3 through 5 
eleven of head starts 1300 programs participated including 
four in baltimore md and one each in winder ga deridder la 
new york city lexington ky toledo ohio las cruces nm and 
dayton ohio 
head start was used because of its emphasis on providing 
equity for kids from lowincome families said thouvenelle vice 
president of mobius corp which developed new software after 
evaluating the program 
she said the software meets the guidelines of the national 
association for the education of young children as being 
developmentally appropriate association officials take no 
position on computers in preschool 
our major concern was whether or not computers were 
applicable or would work for preschool children 3 and 4 years 
old said thouvenelle a second concern she said was whether 
young children can use computers as a tool the same way they use 
blocks or easel painting 
each of the 44 classrooms participating in the experiment had 
two computers that shared a printer mouse and a large 
touchsensitive device known as the powerpad thouvenelle said the 
powerpad is important to young children who often do not have the 
fine motor skills needed to hold a pen or pencil 
the computers ran a program called kidsway which came equipped 
with voice cards in the native language of the parents of the 
children who participated such as spanish navajo swahili and 
japanese 
a key finding said thouvenelle is that computers should be 
available and accessible to youngsters in the classroom the same 
as reading materials art work blocks sandbox and other socalled 
learning center areas preschoolers should not be marched down the 
hall to a computer laboratory she said 
she said a lack of teacher training and support remains a key 
drawback to the program 
winnie porter a 12year teaching veteran of kindergarten 
through fifth grade in san francisco is against pushing academics 
too early in kindergarten computers she said are good as long 
as kids are allowed to explore with them and they are not forced on 
them 
i think children could learn what they would learn from a 
computer as they would learn from other things said pat 
wynneevans who retired last year as a san francisco teacher 
with many school districts plagued by tight budgets lindley 
the south colby principal said if i had to make a financial 
decision between buying big blocks for 400500 and a computer for 
850 id go with the big blocks every time 
kids need active learning computers are not 
multidimensional also you want children using their imagination 
rather than looking at a screen lindley said 
</TEXT>
