<TEXT>
in this dusty village progress is not a 
question of telephones or television it is a matter of water 
stanislaw szablowski and his neighbors had to truck water in 
every day for years their wells were too shallow and tainted even 
for their livestock and crops 
like more than 70 percent of polish villages zastawie had no 
running water recent health ministry tests of the farmyard wells 
villagers depend on throughout poland found the water in 67 percent 
was too polluted to use 
i dont have to tell you the impact of the lack of enough 
clean water on the quality of life on the amount of work for 
women on hygiene on farm productivity said maria stolzman a 
member of parliament 
her water supply foundation led by the roman catholic church 
helped zastawie build a deepwell pumping station that brought 
plentiful fresh water to the 31 farms in august 
polands water crisis also affects urban areas where more than 
half the supply comes from surface water so contaminated that 
experts say it should not have been collected in the first place 
of the 4500 health ministry tests made on city water systems in 
1989 only 376 percent found good water 
we are really struggling said eugenia koblakkolinska 
deputy director of the environment ministrys water department 
everything that can be done on paper regulations 
theoretical research preparation of plans and progress is 
already worked out what we lack is a way to put it into practice 
the new technologies the money 
eastern europe after communism is revealing a horror of 
pollution that was created by heavy industry and untamed by concern 
for the environment 
the nations of the former soviet bloc have neither the expertise 
nor money to reverse the decades of destruction and their efforts 
for economic development often compete with environmental 
protection 
there is optimism however that the change to market economics 
will provide governments newly focused on environmental hazards 
with the ability to fight wanton polluters 
under the old system stateowned factories subsidized by the 
national treasury could afford the modest fines occasionally 
imposed for pollution the fines have been increased by up to 27 
times however and will be much more important to industries 
forced to survive in capitalist competition 
our minister made an ultimatum to a large group of factories 
either you will do something for environmental protection 
during a certain period of time or the factory will cease to 
exist mrs koblakkolinska said the factories still cannot 
believe that something like this might happen 
pollution fighters look with some hope at offers from western 
nations to provide environmental help as part of their aid 
programs 
what they offer us credits with very low interest and some 
modern technologies this is all very interesting mrs 
koblakkolinska said then added but credits have to be paid 
back 
years of pollution of polands water supply are documented in 
handwritten ledgers stacked in the health and environment 
ministries 
in lomza province northeast of warsaw for example only 66 
percent of 280 wells tested in 1989 had acceptable water in 
slupsk a baltic province 40 percent of the 265 wells tested were 
polluted 
communist officials did not act on the information or make it 
public a regime unable to provide jobs housing and food tended to 
dismiss environmental controls as luxuries 
under communist censorship the information about polluted water 
might have been known to a certain very narrow circle of 
people said alicja lopatek a health ministry sanitary 
inspector but it could not come into the open 
reports by the health and environment ministries say 
thirtyfive percent of river water is not even fit for 
industrial use polands main river the vistula running from the 
southern mountains to the baltic is unfit for any use for more 
than half its length 
warsaw is the only european capital without a sewage treatment 
plant and there are none in such other major cities as lodz 
bialystock and radom 
nearly half the 800 small cities and towns lack water 
purification systems environmental officials estimate poland needs 
1900 major sewage treatment plants in towns and cities and 8300 
in rural areas at a total cost of 20 billion to 25 billion 
half the nitrogen deposited in the baltic comes from poland 
along with a large share of other pollutants polands baltic 
resorts are closed to swimmers and its fishing catch is 
questionable prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki said curbing the 
pollution poses many problems and may even be unrealistic 
without significant technological and financial support from 
abroad 
water pumped from polands coal mines is so salty when it pours 
into rivers that it kills biological life and corrodes machinery 
lack of purification systems exacerbates the health threat of 
polluted water 
the filter stations are oldfashioned said stanislaw 
sadanski a health ministry water expert some were built in the in 
the 1920s and 1930s he said and the one in warsaw is 100 years 
old 
mrs lopatek of the ministry said local water systems 
generally dont have any equipment for cleaning water and the 
worst situation is with the wells public and private even on the 
outskirts of warsaw people are using wells 
shallow wells collect surface water that picks up chemicals 
human and animal waste and other contaminants the answer is 
deepwell water facilities with purification and sewage systems 
if you are a mother with a child it may be shocking to hear 
the pollution standard is exceeded by 10 times but if you have 
no other water what do you do sadanski said 
</TEXT>
