<TEXT>
us and soviet negotiators aiming toward an 
early 1991 summit in moscow are tackling the remaining obstacles 
to a treaty on strategic weapons 
after clearing away three major roadblocks to the strategic arms 
reduction treaty or start officials say experts from both sides 
will meet friday in washington to work on remaining technical 
issues they involve inspections to verify treaty compliance and 
telemetry data from ballistic missile testing 
those areas of disagreement still could block completion of the 
treaty but one us official said they are not enough for anyone 
to fall on their sword over 
the negotiators have made significant progress over the past 
month by agreeing to limit soviet backfire bombers that would be 
outside the start treaty itself to allow us nuclear programs 
with britain to continue and to restrict the launch and payload 
weight of the soviets modernized groundbased ss18 missiles 
said an official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the white house is holding off on preparations for president 
bushs trip to moscow anticipated for january saying the 
president will go only if the start treaty is ready to sign 
the treaty aims to cut us and soviet longrange nuclear 
weapons by 30 percent scrapping hundreds of warheads 
secretary of state james a baker iii and soviet foreign 
minister eduard shevardnadze will meet in houston next monday and 
tuesday to hash out the remaining issues and shevardnadze will fly 
to washington to meet with bush on wednesday 
on the three big stumbling blocks recently resolved 
the united states agreed that the soviet backfire bomber can be 
counted separately from the overall start limits of 1600 heavy 
bombers and ballistic missiles the soviets are allowed to retain 
said an official close to the talks 
the source declined to say how many backfires would be permitted 
under the politically binding letter that will be outside the 
treaty itself the soviets have an estimated 355 backfires now 
according to the international institute for strategic studies a 
londonbased think tank 
the soviets agreed to continued us nuclear programs with 
britain as long as those programs are not seen as upsetting the 
overall strategic balance the cooperation primarily involves 
technology and missiles the united states provides for british 
submarines 
the negotiators agreed that any modernized ss18 could not have 
the capability to carry heavier payloads including warheads than 
the current ss18 the treaty however would not limit 
modernization such as improved accuracy or fuel efficiency or 
alteration in the types of warheads 
under the pact the soviets would cut the number of ss18s by 
half to 154 
us officials said the remaining issues involve 
monitoring of production facilities for mobile ballistic 
missiles the two nations disagree on where in the missile 
construction process the monitoring should be allowed the united 
states wants assurances for early inspection of soviet ss24 
missiles which have 10 warheads while the soviets have insisted 
that inspection of final assembly is sufficient 
to what extent each side must provide uncoded telemetry from 
testing of ballistic missiles so that the other can interpret the 
data and verify compliance with the treatys restrictions on 
missile performance 
whether the soviets will be allowed to inspect the b2 bomber 
to ensure it is not equipped to carry longrange cruise missiles 
armed with nuclear warheads 
</TEXT>
