<TEXT>
in four months the bush administration has 
reversed itself on whether economic pressure can force saddam 
hussein to give up his conquest of kuwait 
the president and his people have gone from saying sanctions 
might work to saying sanctions were biting to saying they wont 
do the job 
the turning point the assertion that sanctions wont budge 
saddam came abruptly this week after last weeks united nations 
vote imposing a jan 15 deadline for withdrawing 
just as president bush and his advisers began publicly 
abandoning hope on the worth of sanctions others found them to be 
a promising alternative to war if given time to work 
two former chairmen of the joint chiefs of staff air force gen 
david jones and adm william crowe told the senate armed services 
committee last week that sanctions could achieve their goal in 12 
to 18 months 
it is dead wrong to say that iraq is not being hurt crowe 
testified it is being damaged severely the issue is not 
whether an embargo will work but whether we have the patience to 
let it take effect 
former defense secretary james schlesinger said sanctions 
already had reduced iraqs economic activity by 40 percent 
democrats generally endorsed those views 
after bush imposed sanctions on aug 2 the day saddams army 
took over kuwait he expressed increasing confidence that economic 
pressure supported worldwide would force saddam back 
eight days after the invasion bush told reporters listen 
id love to see the economic sanctions be so successful that the 
us forces could be withdrawn and i think they will be 
successful but i just cant my problem is i just cant estimate 
the time right now how long it will take 
five days later addressing defense department employees during 
a visit to the pentagon bush said sanctions are working 
and the following day after meeting jordans king hussein at 
kennebunkport maine the president said sanctions were taking 
hold i dont think one can sustain true international isolation 
for long especially when you depend on the outside world for a lot 
of your goods he said 
on aug 28 briefing members of congress the president said 
the united nations sanctions are in effect and have been working 
remarkably well even on a voluntary basis 
and on sept 11 in an address to a joint session of congress 
iraq is feeling the heat we continue to hope that iraqs 
leaders will recalculate just what their aggression has cost them 
they are cut off from world trade unable to sell their oil and 
only a tiny fraction of goods gets through i cannot predict 
just how long it will take to convince iraq to withdraw from 
kuwait sanctions will take time to have their full intended 
effect 
then last thursday at the united states behest the security 
council authorized the use of force after jan 15 to compel iraqs 
expulsion from kuwait 
almost at once the administration line on sanctions changed 
defense secretary dick cheney was first there is no guarantee 
that sanctions will force him saddam out of kuwait he 
testified monday he can ride them out 
bush visiting uruguay on tuesday elaborated on the new theme 
ive not been one who has been convinced that sanctions alone 
will bring him to his senses he said while adding that the 
measures were having some effect 
the best chance for peace is for him saddam to understand 
that all means all means necessary will be used against 
him the president said 
secretary of state james a baker iii drove the point home 
wednesday nobody can ever tell you that sanctions alone can 
force saddam hussein out of kuwait i am personally very 
pessimistic that they will 
and cia director william webster said our judgment has been 
and continues to be that there is no assurance or guarantee that 
economic hardhips will compel saddam to change his policies or 
lead to internal unrest that would threaten his regime 
the administrations change could be intended to send saddam the 
message that the united states was ruling out all possibilities 
except the use of force for settling the dispute 
or it could be intended to send that message to the american 
people to prepare them for going to war 
the change of signal is clear its purpose is not 
 
editors note mike feinsilber has covered events in washington 
since 1968 
