<TEXT>
a federal reserve survey of the nations 
economic pulse finds business conditions either declining or 
growing weakly in every region of the country as november came to 
an end 
the beige book survey released wednesday showed retail sales 
down in virtually all 12 of the central banks districts 
manufacturing conditions weakened in most districts and most 
districts also reported continued sluggishness in construction 
demand for business loans softened in many areas at the same 
time banks were tightening their standards for making loans 
on balance business conditions display a weaker pattern 
than a similar survey conducted in midoctober that found either 
slow growth or an actual decline in economic activity in the fed 
districts 
in one of the few bright spots agriculture is reported to 
have been doing very well a summary of the survey said crop 
yields have been good and livestock prices have been high 
the report was the latest piece of evidence that the economy has 
weakened in recent months to the point that many economists say it 
now is in a recession 
manufacturers in particular expressed concern about business 
prospects for the coming months the survey found 
the majority of manufacturers contacted in the boston district 
expect a national recession lasting two to four quarters the 
report said business leaders contacted in the san francisco 
district expect continued deterioration in the national economy 
automobile sales were reported to have weakened particularly in 
the cleveland chicago and st louis districts dallas was an 
exception 
the pessimism however was not universal 
philadelphia manufacturers expect modest improvements over the 
next six months and manufacturers in the richmond district were 
less pessimistic about prospects than they had been a month ago 
the report said 
and soft domestic demand was partially offset by strong export 
orders 
despite the weakness inventories were described as under 
control an excessive increase in inventories could mean job 
layoffs as industries cut production in an attempt to reduce 
backlogs 
nevertheless several districts report a decline in consumer 
and business confidence and many refer to expectations of continued 
diminution in economic activity the survey found 
retail sales apparently have weakened in almost all the 
districts the report said most districts report that 
retailers were pessimistic about sales prospects for the christmas 
season as well as for 1991 
most districts also reported continued sluggishness in 
construction activity 
residential construction continued to be weak with several 
districts citing a glut of houses for resale the report said 
nonresidential construction is also reported to be generally 
weak 
however there are bright spots it continued new york 
reports a recent pickup in office leasing activity in downtown 
manhattan chicago reports that construction slowdowns are not 
universal and that development continues in communities outside 
major metropolitan areas minneapolis reports a recent rebound 
in construction activity 
but the report said activity in the financial sector generally 
was slower 
several districts report a decline in consumer and business 
loan demand it said almost all districts also report some 
tightening by banks of business loan terms particularly for 
construction and land development 
none of the districts reported any major problems with 
inflation although reports of price increases varied in fact the 
strong agricultural production contributed to lower crop prices 
although this adversely affected farmer incomes in some areas 
the report was written at the federal reserve bank of 
minneapolis based on information collected before nov 26 the 
report was prepared for the dec 17 meeting of the federal open 
market committee the fed arm responsible for setting monetary 
policy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

