<TEXT>
president hussain muhammad ershad who 
has promised to resign after widespread protests against his 
government dissolved parliament on thursday after lifting a state 
of emergency 
staterun radio announced the dissolution of parliament but gave 
no reason parliament had been expected to remain in session until 
saturday to ratify ershads successor who would govern in a 
caretaker capacity until new elections 
constitutional experts and wellplaced opposition sources said 
ershad would swear in his own successor 
they said this method of transition of power was chosen because 
it appeared parliament would not be able to summon a majority to 
endorse the caretaker leader supreme court chief justice 
shahabuddin ahmed 
the sources speaking on condition of anomnymity said the 
swearingin might take place later thursday 
twothirds of parliaments members belong to ershads jatiya 
party many have been reluctant to appear in public for fear of 
being attacked by antiershad activists 
some jatiya party offices and officials residences around the 
country have been stoned or ransacked in the past week the 
dissolved parliament was seated in 1986 elections called 
fraudulent by observers that ershad also won 
ershad lifted the state of emergency late wednesday eight days 
after he imposed it because of increasingly violent demonstrations 
for his removal 
but the street protests continued despite the deployment of 
army troops and a curfew that was supposed to keep people indoors 
on tuesday night ershad bowed to the groundswell of opposition 
and said he would step down as soon as a temporary successor was 
chosen 
opposition leaders sheik hasina and khaleda zia agreed 
wednesday night on shahabuddin a career lawyer and judge with a 
reputation as a political independent the two women led the 
sevenweek campaign to oust ershad a former army general who took 
power in a bloodless 1982 coup 
ershads announcement that he would resign ended an 
oftenviolent campaign for his ouster the opposition claims at 
least 100 people were killed by security forces since the 
emergency the government says only six people died 
ershad who only a few weeks ago had confidently predicted he 
would be reelected in the spring caved in to the oppositions 
demands with an abruptness that stunned the country 
antiershad demonstrations had become routine in recent years 
but the latest round were marked by unprecedented unity and 
spontaneity 
as the protests snowballed eight years of rumors and discontent 
over what was perceived as ershads arrogance and tolerance of 
corruption burst out of private drawing rooms into the streets 
the presidents downfall was hastened by a wave of resignations 
in support of the opposition hundreds of doctors professors 
civil servants merchant seamen and at least 19 parliament members 
of his jatiya party resigned from their jobs in protest against 
ershad 
on wednesday a student leader was killed and two other people 
were injured by security guards when they attempted to storm the 
home of a highranking government official in a northern town 
several thousand people assembled at dhaka airport demanding 
that airport authorities stop ershad or other government officials 
if they tried to flee the country 
but there was no indication that any government official was 
planning to leave ershad spent wednesday in his home and in an 
office deep in the wellguarded military cantonment in dhaka and 
canceled all appointments 
a senior member of his cabinet who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said ershad was still in charge of the government other 
sources said the military was still taking orders from ershad 
mrs zia and hasina appealed to their followers for calm they 
said the effort to end ershads rule was not yet over and they 
warned the president of the peoples wrath if he reneged on his 
promise to resign 
addressing 50000 cheering and chanting followers at a rally 
hasina said although ershad announced that he had resigned in 
fact he is still in power 
mrs zia echoed those concerns at another gathering accusing 
ershad of conspiring to stay in power 
let there be no doubt that people will fight until they have 
achieved the victory and ousted the autocratic government she 
said 
on wednesday staterun media let hasina and mrs zia address 
the people for the first time 
the two women have been agitating for ershads ouster since he 
took power but their political differences thwarted any lasting 
campaign 
then in october the opposition was galvanized by ershads 
announcement that he would be a candidate in june presidential 
elections 
mrs zia and hasina have said they have buried their 
differences but they still have not spelled out their stands on 
constitutional changes or on other domestic or foreign issues 
hasina is the daughter of sheik mujibur rahman bangladeshs 
first president mrs zia is the widow of another former president 
ziaur rehman both men were assassinated 
ershad is the countrys ninth president since it gained 
independence from pakistan in 1971 like all of his predecessors 
he was installed by military action 
