the two women who forced a change of 
government this week have one thing in common they were thrust 
into politics by assassinations that deprived them of the men who 
had the most influence on their lives 
both men were presidents of bangladesh 
apart from that sheik hasina and khaleda zia share little 
except a dogged determination to oust president hussain muhammad 
ershad the ninth president in 19 years and like all his 
predecessors installed by military might 
their personal and political rivalry had long been a stumbling 
block in their shared goal of ousting ershad 
mrs zia asked once why she couldnt patch up her differences 
with hasina said frostily two days ago i invited her to tea 
she didnt come 
hasina and mrs zia had usually boycotted national elections for 
the presidency and parliament 
but finally they were forced to face the fastapproaching 
reality ershad planned to seek election in june for another 5year 
term and might win unless they mounted a joint campaign 
both women had long vowed not to run against him charging that 
he would would rig the elections to ensure his own victory 
changing their minds would have meant backing down on what they had 
called a matter of principle 
neither was ready to run unless the other did and even if they 
both ran ershad might have emerged the victor in a threeway 
contest 
since the one thing they could agree on was getting rid of 
ershad they concentrated on that as they never had before their 
street rallies and nationwide strikes took on a life of their own 
drawing in people who previously had been content to sit at home 
and gripe about ershad without taking public action 
after seven weeks of strikes and demonstrations ershad said 
tuesday that he would resign as soon as his replacement was chosen 
the question of who will eventually emerge as bangladeshs top 
leader hasina or mrs zia or a political compromise or darkhorse 
candidate is unanswered so is the matter of what political 
course hasina and mrs zia will pursue while they hold the 
momentum 
hasina 43 presides over the awami league and seven allied 
parties which are slightly leftofcenter 
mrs zia 46 is the leader of the bangladesh nationalist party 
which is grouped with six other centrist parties 
hasina inherited the awami league leadership after her father 
bangladeshs first president sheik mujibur rahman was 
assassinated in a military coup in 1975 
hasina was in germany at the time except for a sister who also 
was abroad hasinas entire family was wiped out in the coup her 
father mother three brothers two sistersinlaw two uncles and 
a cousin were all slain by the army officers who stormed into the 
family home 
hasinas office is her fathers library just across the hall 
from the stairs where his bloodstains have been preserved and fresh 
flowers are placed daily 
mrs zias husband president ziaur rahman was an army general 
who took power in a 1977 coup and was assassinated four years 
later 
despite their common personal tragedies hasina never warmed to 
mrs zia a charismatic woman who strikes the sort of empathy with 
crowds that hasina has never achieved 
hasina harbors suspicions that gen zia might have had a role in 
the coup that killed her father according to her closest 
associates 
besides that the two women have fundamental political 
differences hasina prefers a parliamentary system of government 
where power goes to the party that wins the most seats and whose 
leader automatically becomes prime minister 
mrs zia favors the presidential system wheretthe voters elect 
an individual leader 
hasinas main strength is that her awami league is believed to 
have a larger and betterorganized grass roots following than mrs 
zias bangladesh nationalist party 
but mrs zia inspires the crowds by her mere presence she 
exudes warmth and glamor with discreet makeup and jewels and 
silken saris 
hasina with her wirerimmed spectacles and practical cotton 
saris appears like a lecturer facing a classroom of dutiful 
students the dry wit she displays in small gatherings seldom comes 
across in public 
both were brought into politics by supporters of their 
assassinated menfolk 
after her father was killed hasina spent six years in 
selfexile in india where her husband nuclear scientist wazed ali 
miah was studying 
she was elected head of the awami league before she ever 
returned to bangladesh although she says she had been tutored in 
politics since childhood 
mrs zia was pressured to enter politics by her late husbands 
followers who were looking for someone to unite his party 
but both women evolved into dominant leaders in their own right 
she gets her own way when the question of party decision 
comes said a senior leader of mrs zias party speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
hasina has a similar reputation within her party where she is 
periodically at odds with the older leaders she surrounds herself 
with young people who support her in the internal party fights 
against the senior leaders 
