<TEXT>
the suspicion that profits influence the way 
doctors treat patients got some support today from a study showing 
that those who make money on xrays take four times as many of 
them researchers say 
the study based on a review of insurance records compared 
doctors who owned their own office xray and ultrasound machines 
with those who send their patients to other specialists for xrays 
doctors make a profit on each image they take on their own 
equipment but make nothing when they send patients to other 
experts 
the study published in the new england journal of medicine 
found that those who owned their own machines took four times as 
many xrays and ultrasound scans for such routine conditions as 
colds and backaches 
it also found that doctors who owned their own equipment charged 
considerably more for them than did outside radiologists 
although the study could not determine precisely why these 
doctors did more xrays one has to wonder whether its an issue 
of having these machines and realizing that incomes can be 
increased by their utilization said dr bruce j hillman who 
directed the study at the university of arizona 
ethical standards require that doctors put patients health 
ahead of their own financial interests 
e haavi morreim a philosopher at the university of tennessee 
college of medicine said there may be other explanations for the 
higher xray use aside from the obvious possibility that frankly 
there is money to be made in them there hills 
there is the simple fact that when something is available 
its easy to use it often she said when you have a hammer 
everything looks like a nail 
physicians who own xray machines were critical of the study and 
its implications dr james weber a family practitioner in 
jacksonville ark said doctors who do more xrays may be 
practicing better medicine 
the assumption is inferred that these tests are ordered to 
benefit the physician rather than the patient he said i can 
tell you that wherever you go in the country that may be true of 
less than 1 percent of practicing physicians the vast majority of 
physicians have their patients interests at heart 
dr j harold morris an internist in kansas city said doctors 
who buy this equipment may take more xrays because they fear 
malpractice or simply because they are by training more inclined 
to seek test results 
the study was based on computerized records of 65517 doctor 
visits by privately insured patients who worked for several 
companies mostly in the midwest 
the researchers compared the number of xrays and ultrasound 
scans used by doctors who treated patients for stuffy noses 
pregnancy low back pain and for men difficulty urinating 
