<TEXT>
nearly a year after a us invasion 
installed president guillermo endara the government remains so 
weak that it needed american gis to put down an attempted mutiny 
led by a disaffected officer 
wednesdays rebellion in a panamanian sergeant was killed was 
the most serious challenge mounted to the yearold endara 
government and a setback in us efforts to foster a stable 
government 
washington agreed just over a decade ago to cede control over 
the panama canal at the end of the century 
the bush administration removed dictator gen manuel antonio 
noriega last dec 20 in an invasion it said was justified because 
it put a democratically elected politician in office and fostered a 
return to wellbeing in panama 
but the economy remains depressed despite endaras efforts to 
revive it he has cut government spending sold off moneylosing 
state companies and instituted other belttightening measures 
about 30000 of panamas 100000 public workers held a 24hour 
strike wednesday called by the coordinator of unions an umbrella 
group that includes noriega supporters 
strike leaders threaten longer strikes to continue pressing for 
job security easing austerity and wage raises which endara says 
panamas economy based on small canal revenues and a meager 
agriculture cannot afford 
workers pay is still low about 200000 people out of a 
population of 24 million remain jobless at 35 billion panamas 
foreign debt is the highest per capita in latin america 
on tuesday afternoon while about 40000 public workers were 
holding a street demonstration the former deputy national police 
chief escaped from jail on the pacific island of nao 
retired col eduardo herrera hassan who was awaiting trial on 
charges of plotting against the government flew to his former 
panama city headquarters where the government says he tried to 
organize an uprising 
herrera accused the government of humiliating members of the 
national police the entity created in january to replace noriegas 
disbanded defense forces the 13000strong force includes many 
former defense forces soldiers 
herrera had been named national police deputy chief but was 
removed in august and jailed in october 
after his escape he radioed units nationwide for support but 
except for a few dozen supporters the national police remained 
loyal to endara 
endara summoned a special joint uspanamanian task force to 
quell the mutiny the force of 500 troops led by american 
soldiers had been helping the hitherto untrustworthy police keep 
order since the invasion 
their attempts to rally panamanian troops unsuccessful herrera 
and his coconspirators tried to flee military headquarters and a 
panamanian sergeant was killed and three civilians wounded in the 
shooting that followed 
herrera a hardnosed veteran trained in israeli and the us 
military schools was captured along with 35 others fifteen rebels 
were at large 
some 120000 us troops are stationed in the country and the 
joint patrolling agreement they have with the panamanians expires 
at the end december due to the political uncertainty and questions 
about the loyalty of the national police it appears that agreement 
could be extended 
tuesday was the first time since 1925 that a panamanian 
president formally asked us troops to help restore order the 
last time they helped quell riots to protest increases in housing 
rents 
us troops werent invited last december they just roared in 
from bases inside and outside panama crushed the defense forces 
and flew noriega to miami to stand trial on drug trafficking and 
money laundering charges 
some 370 panamanians were killed in the fighting then 
endara who had won handily in may 1989 elections that noriega 
annulled was sworn in as president just as us troops made their 
move 
corruption remains widespread in panama having thrived during 
the years of military rule that began when gen omar torrijos 
seized power in 1968 militarydominated regimes succeeded his 
dictatorship when he died in a mysterious plane crash july 31 
1981 
seven puppet civilian governments came and went at noriegas 
whim while he wielded power as defense forces chief in the 1980s 
a cousin close to torrijos herrera was also a noriega crony 
until the two had a falling out and the dictator packed him off as 
military attache to israel when herrera returned in january 
endara put him in charge of demilitarizing the police 
herrera told reporters shortly before his arrest wednesday that 
he was not leading a coup but trying to dramatize the disaffection 
of the former military turned policemen 
many of them are known to miss the power and the perks they once 
had no military force was created after noriegas defense forces 
were disbanded 
panama seized independence from colombia in 1903 with us 
warships standing off its coasts by to help after that the us 
government built ran and owned the panama canal 
in 1978 the treaties ceding the canal to panama 2000 were 
ratified and panama became its titular owner 
the two governments now jointly administer the waterway and the 
us southern command keeps its troops on 11 military bases along 
the canals shores under the treaties the bases are to be 
eliminated by the year 2000 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
alina guerrero is panama correspondent for the 
associated press 
</TEXT>
