lewis greene flecks of blood clinging to his 
glasses still looked a little dazed as he watched workers hose 
down the rhinoceros house at the audubon zoo 
greene had just lost if not a loved one a longtime 
companion jessie a 32yearold african white rhinoceros died as 
veterinarians removed part of her horn in hopes the operation would 
enable them to breed her before she was too old 
both of our males have very small horns and both females have 
large horns we think that prevented them from mating the females 
with larger horns would spar with the males and were able to keep 
them away said greene the zoo keeper in charge of rhinos 
other zoos that have had the problem have had good luck 
reducing the females horn greene said putting them on equal 
footing so to speak 
because rhinoceroses in the wild are disappearing zoos are 
trying to breed those they have in accordance with an international 
species survival plan 
all of the five surviving species are endangered because of 
habitat destruction and illegal hunting especially for their 
horns said curt burnette audubons general curator 
the horns made of matted hair are considered an aphrodisiac in 
the far east where they sell for as much as 18000 a pound 
their situation in the wild is from bad to critical 
burnette said of the five species the white is the most 
plentiful there are probably several thousand of them the 
sumatran rhino probably numbers in the dozens in 10 years i doubt 
there will be any rhinos existing in the wild 
jessies biological clock was ticking away and officials hoped 
to breed her before it was too late since the four rhinoceroses at 
audubon were all caught in the wild adding their genes to the 
genetic pool of captured rhinos would improve the longterm chances 
of the species surviving greene said 
short term there will be rhinos in zoos but longterm their 
survival even there could be in jeopardy if only 20 percent of 
the captive rhinos breed as the years go by therell be fewer and 
fewer that can reproduce greene said 
the operation to reduce jessies horn was considered safe 
burnette said the animal had been anesthetized previously without 
difficulty he said 
it was low risk and we were willing to take a small risk 
because we have to burnette said her genes werent crucial 
but they were important since she was captured in the wild the 
offspring would be new to the captive breeding stock 
after the horn was trimmed the four veterinarians were doing 
some blood tests and an ultrasound test on the animals 
reproductive organs when she stopped breathing burnette said 
a 12hour necropsy was done to determine what caused the rhino 
to die burnette said it might take weeks before results were 
known 
jessie still might contribute to the overall genetic pool 
burnette said veterinarians harvested unfertilized eggs which 
will be frozen in hopes of fertilizing them and implanting them in 
another rhinoceros 
thats just a hope at this time burnette said the 
technique hasnt been perfected its kind of like having your body 
frozen when you die and hope theyll be able to bring you back 
later but when something is so close to disappearing you take 
every chance you can to prevent that 
