<TEXT>
a senior energy department official accused 
japan on thursday of hoarding crude oil in the months after iraqs 
invasion of kuwait despite agreement among most consuming nations 
to draw down stockpiles and ease supply problems 
linda stuntz an energy department deputy under secretary for 
policy and planning said she expects the issue to be raised next 
week at a meeting of the governing board of the international 
energy agency 
the parisbased agency is responsible for coordinating responses 
by oil consuming nations in an oil supply emergency 
if everybody in the world did what japan is doing we would 
have a much more serious problem than we do prices would be a lot 
higher said ms stuntz in remarks to a group of reporters 
she later said in an interview that she did not want to 
overstate the concern but added that japans actions raise 
questions about the success of future cooperative activities among 
consuming nations in response to oil supply shocks 
ms stuntz said that in the months after the iraqi invasion of 
kuwait last august us oil companies and most companies in europe 
drew down crude oil stocks in order to keep supplies adequate 
without having to dramatically increase imports 
but she said the japanese rather than drawing down crude oil 
stocks after the loss of iraqi and kuwaiti oil elected instead to 
continue importing at high levels and in fact increased imports 
to meet additional demand 
that is stockpiling she said something the united states 
and other consuming nations had sought to prevent to ease the 
immediate shock of losing 43 million barrels of oil a day as a 
result of the iraqkuwait crisis 
ms stuntz said that despite increasing consumer demand us 
imports were 12 percent lower in september and 25 percent lower in 
october than they were last july before the iraqi invasion 
because us refineries were relying on existing stocks 
in october japan imported 33 percent more oil than it did in 
july she said 
what does this mean for future cooperative activities she 
asked 
</TEXT>
