<TEXT>
the head of the federal communications 
commission announced on thursday an endeavor to squeeze future 
technologies such as highdefinition tv personal phones and 
digital radio onto the nations crowded airwaves 
fcc chairman alfred sikes noting that congress and his agency 
are making decisions today that will affect american lifestyles and 
economic competitiveness well into the 21st century said the fcc 
will initiate a search next year for frequencies to satisfy the 
voracious appetites of new radiobased technologies 
my ultimate goal will be to create a new spectrum reserve for 
emerging technologies sikes said in what was good news for a 
host of wouldbe broadcasters and telecommunications companies that 
are waging a fierce battle for wave space 
but in a bit of bad news for existing licensees sikes warned 
that locating spectrum to accommodate new technologies could not be 
done without some pain to incumbents 
if we are to have sufficient spectrum to meet projected new 
technology needs some of the incumbents will have to find new 
homes sikes said in a speech to the practicing law institute 
he added however that the legitimate needs of incumbents must 
be considered and that any comprehensive program will have to be 
implemented over a period of years 
new technologies such as hdtv and pocketsized goanywhere 
telephones are expected to arrive worldwide by the end of the 
decade and dramatically change todays communications systems 
digital broadcasting is another area of promise in which 
compactdisc quality sound may be available from traditional radio 
stations or from new satellite companies 
these technologies will require a radical overhaul of existing 
transmission and receiving systems creating new jobs and business 
opportunities and are expected to play a crucial role in 
determining the nations economic wellbeing in the next century 
the house this year passed a bill by rep john dingell dmich 
that would force the government to relinquish for private use about 
a third 200 mhz of the radio spectrum that is allocated 
exclusively for government use the bill did not get through the 
senate 
advocates of highdefinition television personal phones and 
digital broadcasting are squabbling over spectrum now held by uhf 
broadcasters cellular telephone companies and microwave users such 
as police and fire departments mobile radio dispatchers the space 
industry railroads and utilities 
new and more spectrumefficient radio technology promises to 
ease the pain somewhat of reallocation of spectrum and 
technological advances also promise the ability for different users 
to share space 
but something will have to give somewhere as sikes noted since 
there is only so much wave space 
the creation of spectrum reserve will not be without costs 
sikes said but the benefits to the public of facilitating new 
communications services will be dramatic 
he noted that in europe and japan important chunks of the 
airwaves already have been set aside for these emerging 
technologies 
we need to do at least as much as our international trading 
partners sikes said 
sikes said the commission also will be looking at how to deal 
with proposals to create new multipleuse technologies such as 
linking satellite and cellular systems together allowing telephone 
companies to provide cable tv service over phone lines or allowing 
cable and mobile communications companies to link up as an 
alternative to private or public phone networks 
