<TEXT>
ignorance about female biology still impedes 
the treatment of breast cancer and other diseases of women a panel 
of scientists said thursday 
theres no research on the normal breast said dr susan 
love an author and professor of surgery at harvard therefore 
we dont have a clue when carcinogens are acting 
yet breast cancer will strike one woman in 10 in her lifetime 
and will kill 44000 this year she said 
it is appalling that in 1990 we have little or no information 
on the natural course of the endocrine and tissue changes that 
occur during menopause said barbara sherwin of mcgill 
university 
the two medical expas that medical professionals consider 
closely but also look beyond the biological factors unique to women 
such as the menstrual cycle pregnancy and hormonal differences 
they said professionals also need to gather data on individual 
patients social and economic status as risk factors poverty 
raising children alone and on psychosocial factors such as 
depression occupational stress and the multiple demands on women 
as mothers workers and spouses 
special centers should be established at academic research 
facilities to study the interactions and complexities that have 
an impact on womens health said dr susan blumenthal chief of 
the behavioral medicine program at the national institute of mental 
health 
that women generally live longer than men poses challenges in 
itself noted dr william hazzard chairman of the medical school 
at wake forest university and spokeswoman for the cardiovascular 
panel 
for example he said heart disease accounts for more than a 
quarter of all deaths in women in the united states but women 
suffer heart attacks and heart disease later in life and often 
they must endure their suffering alone while men usually have their 
spouses for support he said 
the growing longevity of women also exacerbates ignorance about 
menopause said sherwin changes brought about by menopause account 
for an estimated 250000 hip fractures a year 
another problem that follows menopause urinary incontinence 
accounts for billions of dollars in costs not to mention the 
human misery that results from the problem she said 
panelists in all four fields also agreed on the need for further 
understanding of hormones especially hormonal therapy because of 
their impact on diseases and treatments 
we desperately and urgently need prospective studies of 
postmenopausal hormones and their effects on cardiovascular 
disease on atherosclerosis breast cancer and endometrial 
cancer said love otherwise women cannot make the decisions 
that they need to make 
it may be worth the small increase in breast cancer to 
eliminate the large number of women dying of heart disease but 
until we know what risks were weighing we cant make those kinds 
of decisons 
the panelists reiterated the criticism raised in recent months 
in congress that women are being excluded from clinical research 
and they noted efforts within the federal national institutes of 
health to monitor research grants to be sure women are included 
