the vatican restored diplomatic ties with 
bulgaria thursday thus achieving ties with all members of the 
former warsaw pact and formally ending an era in which the church 
and the east bloc were foes 
the former hardline communist nation had been implicated in an 
attempt to kill pope john paul ii 
in a brief statement the vatican said ties between the holy see 
and bulgaria would be at the ambassadorial level 
diplomatic links were broken in 1949 when the communist 
government prevented the vaticans representative from reentering 
the country 
since democratic revolutions swept eastern europe in the past 18 
months ousting communist governments the vatican has also restored 
ties with czechoslovakia hungary romania and pope john paul iis 
native poland 
also this year ties were forged for the first time with the 
soviet union 
the pope has been invited to visit bulgaria he has already made 
a brief trip to czechoslovakia and is to travelt to hungary in 
1991 
relations between the vatican and bulgaria reached a 
particularly low point after the 1981 assassination attempt on pope 
john paul ii 
italian prosecutors said the plot involved bulgarian agents and 
the soviet kgb a rome court however acquitted three bulgarians 
of conspiracy to murder the pontiff citing lack of evidence 
bulgaria denied involvement in the shooting which was carried 
out by a turk 
catholics make up only around 1 percent of bulgarias population 
of about 9 million 
under bulgarias previous communist government freedom of 
religion was guaranteed by law however most bulgarian christians 
were at least nominal members of the bulgarian orthodox church 
which avoided antagonizing authority 
the country has a large moslem minority but many discontinued 
practice of their religion under pressure from the communist 
government 
