<TEXT>
homicide the leading cause of death among young 
black males has increased by twothirds among that group in four 
years researchers with the national centers for disease control 
reported thursday 
nationwide 2741 black males aged 15 to 24 were homicide 
victims in 1988 cdc epiemiologist dr robert froehlke said 
the killings represent a rate of 1011 for every 100000 black 
males in the age group up 67 percent from the 1984 rate of 606 
the new figures indicate a reversal in a trend that saw 
homicides decrease among young black men in the early 1980s the 
cdc said 
meanwhile rates for females and white males in that age group 
have either stayed essentially the same or in fact decreased a 
little bit froehlke said the disparity between black males 
and other groups has widened even more 
in 1987 the latest year in which complete statistics are 
available young black males homicide rate is some six times 
greater than the rate for all americans aged 1524 among blacks 
the rate was 846 per 100000 compared with 138 per 100000 
froehlke said 
the nations overall homicide rate in 1987 was 85 per 100000 
that year homicides accounted for 42 percent of the deaths of 
black males in that age group 
the cdcs analysis is based on 1987 figures the 1988 
statistics released just last week have not yet been analyzed 
indepth froehlke said 
the homicide problem is getting worse faster for black teenage 
males the cdc said the 1988 homicide rate for black males 1519 
was 768 per 100000 up 99 percent since 1984 the rate for black 
males 2024 was 1272 per 100000 up 53 percent since 1984 
firearm homicides accounted for more than 95 percent of the 
198487 increase in killings of young black males the cdc said 
six areas california florida michigan missouri new york 
and the district of columbia accounted for 51 percent of the 
deaths of young black males in 1987 
those six locations have 29 percent of the nations population 
of black males aged 1524 the cdc said 
in its weekly report the cdc called for more research into ways 
to stop the killings 
research and evaluation efforts have not demonstrated 
effective programmatic approaches to prevent homicide the 
atlantabased agency said 
