<TEXT>
new estimates that the budget deficit is 
soaring past 300 billion will test voters tolerance for federal 
red ink but analysts are divided over whether the record 
shortfalls will blunt congress spending appetite 
the congressional budget office projected thursday that next 
years budget gap will be at least 337 billion the nonpartisan 
budget office blamed the slowing economy and the expensive bailout 
of the nations savings and loans 
that would easily set a record despite the nov 5 enactment of 
a fiveyear package of tax increases and spending cuts designed to 
shrink the deficits by 496 billion in that period 
the record deficit puts one more arrow in the quiver of those 
who would oppose higher spending said carol cox president of 
the committee for a responsible federal budget a bipartisan group 
that studies budget issues there is a political constraint in an 
era of 300 billion deficits when somebody wants to spend even more 
money 
others noted that new budget procedures virtually eliminate the 
current system of acrosstheboard spending cuts if the deficit is 
too high as a result they said large budget gaps may not 
