voters in the nations eighth largest city are 
divided over a referendum designed to help minorities win seats on 
the city council 
supporters of the proposal to create singlemember districts say 
the plan would help ease racial inequities that make it difficult 
for minorites to get elected 
opponents say the referendum would actually resegregate dallas 
they back a plan voters approved last year that called for some 
candidates to be elected by district others by region and one at 
large for the 11member council 
the referendum up for vote saturday has heightened existing 
racial tension in the ethnically diverse city community leaders 
said 
to some this election represents the last chance for peace in 
dallas said roy williams one of two former city council 
candidates who sued the city over its election system saying it 
was discriminatory 
it would be a serious mistake for the city to ignore the 
warning signs widespread frustrations and cynicism in the 
community williams said 
under the existing system instituted in 1975 eight council 
members are elected in individual districts and another three 
including the mayor are elected by voters citywide 
the system voters approved by a 21 margin in august 1989 called 
for 10 candidates to be chosen by district four by region and one 
at large that system was never implemented because a federal judge 
suggested he would rule it unconstitutional 
the system proposed in the referendum calls for the creation of 
14 singlemember districts with a mayor elected at large 
the referendum is being held as part of the settlement of the 
1988 federal lawsuit brought by williams and marvin crenshaw who 
failed in their atlarge council bids 
the men who are both black charged the existing election 
system made it difficult for minorities to win election 
black and hispanic leaders nationwide have long charged that 
atlarge elections dilute minority candidates political power and 
make it difficult for them to win office 
they maintain minorities have a better chance of winning office 
under a political system in which candidates are elected by 
individual districts 
the city proposed the referendum on the newest plan when it 
reached a settlement with williams and crenshaw in august 
although minorities are estimated to make up more than half the 
citys population only two of 11 city council members are black 
and there are no hispanics only one minority a hispanic who no 
longer serves on the council has won an atlarge city council 
election 
if a simple majority of voters approve the plan a commission 
will be set up to draw new district lines next year using 1990 
census figures almost 17000 of the citys 451411 registered 
voters cast absentee ballots as of thursday 
former dallas cowboy quarterback roger staubach is among those 
who support the change youve got to look at where dallas has 
come and how it has treated the representation of minorities 
staubach said it has not been fair 
opponents include city councilman glenn box who said the plan 
is a token quota system that resegregates the city 
we dont become an integrated city with 141 box said 
a poll the dallas morning news published last weekend indicated 
voters were not unified on the issue 
half of the likely voters the newspaper contacted said they 
would support the measure another 30 percent said they would vote 
no and 20 percent were undecided 
there have been no formal estimates of the citys racial makeup 
since the 1980 census when dallas 904078 population was 61 
percent white 26 percent black and 12 hispanic 
the racial breakdown of the 1990 census count of 982250 people 
is expected to show a majority black and hispanic population 
</TEXT>
