<TEXT>
police and prosecutors nationwide unfairly 
target minority offenders in juvenile drug cases said a study 
released thursday by the national center for juvenile justice 
the study said drug prosecutions of whites dropped 15 percent 
from 1985 to 1988 while prosecutions of nonwhites jumped 88 
percent in the same period 
researchers reviewed more than 300000 records in the centers 
national juvenile court archive 
the records described drug and alcohol cases in 841 
jurisdictions across 17 randomly selected states officials said 
the disparity between the number of cases against whites and 
those against nonwhites was alarming said hunter hurst director 
of the pittsburgh center a nonprofit research organization 
partially funded by the us justice department 
the juvenile justice system is rapidly becoming a system 
exclusively for minority offenders hurst said this is one war 
we cannot win by focusing solely on minorities and the poor 
the study said the number of drug cases involving all youths are 
on the rise 
