<TEXT>
a year after sweeping to power 
eastern europes intellectuals face a dilemma how to mesh their 
old job of keeping the national identity with the new one of 
conducting practical politics 
for 40 years these men and women preserved the cultures of 
their nations in spite of communist repression and guarded 
individuality against collectivism 
intellectuals have played a similar role for at least 100 years 
in the region whose 19th century nationalist movements were 
founded by thinkers determined to find places for their nations 
apart from giant alien empires 
when the soviet empire suddenly crumbled last year politics 
fell in many cases to the dissidents and intellectuals the only 
figures sufficiently untainted by communism 
after a deluge of economl be swept out 
a senior aide to president vaclav havel said its fun when 
you can work on the intellectual concepts but its not when you 
get caught up in schedules and routine 
the aide speaking on condition of anonymity reflected a 
certain distaste for daytoday politics that some commentators and 
foreign observers see as a serious flaw 
its sad but theres almost no politician in sight said 
vladimir mlynar a former dissident who now is a journalist at the 
daily lidove noviny 
havel doesnt see this too well because his pet theory is that 
politicians have brought the world to ruin mlynar said 
his problem is that as a dissident he made up this theory of 
moral politics when he became president he found out you must 
behave differently because your opponents behave like politicians 
he would not admit this but hes learning 
the problem is perhaps most acute in czechoslovakia where havel 
and other dissidents went in mere weeks from the underground to the 
presidential castle that dominates pragues skyline 
in poland intellectuals were able to ally with the workers 10 
years ago in solidarity even after solidarity was suppressed real 
politics continued underground 
change also was more gradual in hungary where some dissident 
opposition was tolerated in 1985 the hungarians held partially 
free elections for a communistdominated parliament 
in bulgaria as in czechoslovakia everything seemed to happen 
at once the ouster in a politburo coup of todor zhivkov who had 
led the nation for 35 years caught both the opposition and much of 
the communist party by surprise 
the party had never articulated its internal split between 
reformers and stalinists and the opposition had just begun to 
organize they are still quarreling over who should rule 
only in romania did key intellectuals stand aloof from politics 
largely refusing to join either the technocratdominated national 
salvation front or the opposition 
their attempt to continue acting as the nations conscience 
however drowned in the emotion and intrigues of everyday politics 
one result of the sudden changes and the intellectuals new role 
is a dearth of cultural interest across the region 
we have lost our theme said alex koenigsmark a 
czechoslovak playwright dodging the censors and communist 
oppression used to unite spectators and artists in a kind of 
plot he said now we must search for new identity 
some intellectuals have been slow to abandon what koenigsmark 
called the stalinist warmth of the old system which lured 
artists into conformity by offering the material comforts of 
special holiday homes or guaranteed fees 
tens of thousands of other intellectuals eked out livings in 
undemanding jobs their reward was plenty of free time to read and 
debate existential problems in a fashion that exhilarated 
westerners absorbed in material gain 
financial needs also occupy eastern brains these days 
we have simply no time to read anymore said vasil 
atanassov a bulgarian translator now we have to make money 
this means east european societies are stripped of the very 
people who as mlynar put it should shove the mirror in 
politicians faces so they cannot move outside certain 
boundaries 
in western societies this role is played largely by the media 
free independent media are slow to emerge in eastern europe where 
most people know only totalitarianism 
especially in the balkans a torrent of emotional comment poses 
as free reporting 
even at lidove noviny which existed in the underground it 
often proves difficult for former dissidents to stand back from the 
petty intrigues of daily politics or to criticize friends in power 
collapsing economies add to the woes culture no longer enjoys 
heavy subsidies meaning soaring ticket and book prices that drive 
audiences away 
western pop and pornography long forbidden are touted 
blatantly throughout eastern europe the popular concept that 
freedom equals the absence of control makes it difficult to impose 
limits on such wares 
idealists who could sketch the new identities for which society 
might strive find such a climate unwelcoming 
its quite nice to have visions wrote jaroslav weiss a 
lidove noviny columnist but you have to have money for that 
</TEXT>
