<TEXT>
gone are the goose step the old 
allies the pledge to protect communism from the evil forces of the 
other side gone too is the other side 
the east german soldiers who once stood on the cold war front 
find the front has moved to their flank what once was the enemy 
flag flies over their garrisons old foes are now commanders and 
comrades 
welcome to nato soldier your old mission with the warsaw pact 
is finished so is the warsaw pact 
once pointed defiantly westward the national peoples army now 
wears the uniform of a united german military a more benign entity 
pointed nowhere in particular 
without firing a shot the west german armed forces took over 
their eastern counterpart in a single day then fired most of the 
officers and cut the force almost in half in a matter of weeks 
what has been billed as a merger is essentially a purge the 
remaining soldiers must apply to stay if they are approved they 
will undergo a twoyear probation to determine whether they have 
the right ideological stuff to continue their careers 
for old soldiers like me the generals and commanders it was 
right to dismiss them theres a new command said gerhard 
seifert an ousted communist general who led an engineering corps 
but firing other professional soldiers i think they moved too 
quickly 
seifert lives in wildpark west a village of large homes hidden 
in a forest outside berlin and surrounded by a military complex 
once known as national peoples army defense district no 84 
before world war ii wildpark west was an exclusive resort for 
some of berlins wealthiest people after germany was divided it 
became home to top officers in the east german army 
now wildpark west is esentially a retirement community 
seifert who spent 38 years in the army warmly welcomed a 
visitor and displayed snapshots his wife took on oct 10 the day 
he relinquished his command 
one shows him on a couch in uniform drinking cognac with gen 
eckard jantzen the west german who took over the base outside 
potsdam 18 miles south of berlin 
for years we were painted a portrait of the western soldiers 
as the enemy seifert 59 said jovially but on that day we 
were all military men 
seifert who was 12 when he watched american planes bomb his 
native chemnitz during world war ii said he had no animosity 
toward the west and realized the necessity of his nations 
evolution 
he expressed disappointment however that professional east 
german military personnel were dismissed so quickly 
career soldiers too young for pensions and too old for new 
work face a difficult future seifert said 
the western army also is becoming smaller but has not shrunk so 
dramatically 
to get the four world war ii allies who conquered germany to 
agree to reunification the nation must reduce its total forces to 
370000 by 1994 
on oct 3 unification day west germany had 460000 soldiers 
and the east had 110000 
only 6000080000 now remain in eastern germany and the west 
has about 450000 defense department spokesman walter 
reichenmiller said 
many soldiers in the east have quit or were conscripts who had 
their tours of duty reduced about 25000 most of them officers 
were dismissed for being too close to old regime 
ultimately the goal is 50000 eastern troops and 320000 in the 
west reichenmiller said 
for the soldiers who remain the biggest challenge will be 
thinking differently 
east german soldiers promised to defend communism and were 
subject to rigid external discipline 
west germans in a reaction to nazi brutality have been 
schooled in innere fuehrung or moral leadership a philosophy 
that teaches a code of honor humanity selfdiscipline and 
responsibility 
one of our major concerns is to educate our eastern friends in 
the terms of how we think a military individual should relate to a 
community reichenmiller said 
its a formidable job certainly it wont work with 
everybody but there are enough people there who are young enough 
tolerant enough to learn 
klaus becher a security analyst with the german society for 
foreign politics in cologne said tensions had arisen because 
western officers know little about the men they now command 
its uneasy to say the least he said some of the 
western soldiers look down on their colleagues 
bjorn trauer a 19yearold native of potsdam drafted in 
september served one month in the national peoples army and now 
wears a western uniform 
the western officers are much friendlier he said but i 
think its a shame they had to fire so many of the old officers 
strangely the part of the old east german army with the darkest 
past still remains about 6000 border troops who had orders to 
shoot people fleeing the country remain on duty 
they are removing the border fortifications land mines 
watchtowers and electrical fencing they once monitored 
they will be dismissed once the job is done reichenmiller 
said they have of course a rather bad reputation 
for the east german soldier the last year has been a jarring 
experience 
markus nitschke a former soldier from potsdam was drafted in 
september 1989 just as protests against the old government were 
beginning he said soldiers were given training in riot control 
including how to use nightsticks 
soldiers were asked to sign pledges promising to support the 
police he and several others refused nitschke said and that 
caused problems initially but after honecker fell nobody cared 
any more 
communist party chief erich honecker was forced out in october 
1989 nitschke 20 now is a civil engineering student 
east germans elected a democratic government in march that made 
major changes including the remarkable decision to appoint a 
pacifist preacher rainer eppelmann as defense minister 
he cut the 3year tour of duty in half got rid of the goose 
step that had been the armys trademark and removed the inductees 
pledge to protect communism 
german unification eliminated the national peoples army 
altogether and is now causing the removal from german soil of its 
staunch ally the red army all 380000 soviet soldiers in eastern 
germany must leave within four years 
they are returning to an economically depressed ethnically 
polarized country whose very existence is in question 
there have been widespread reports of soviet soldiers deserting 
selling their guns and uniforms even committing suicide 
i worked with these men all my life seifert said i was 
trained in moscow its tragic whats happening to them 
 
