<TEXT>
according to vice president dan quayles sales 
pitch theres not much wrong with congress that couldnt be fixed 
by putting a 12year limit on house or senate service 
to that critics reply that some of the very ills quayle cited 
would only get worse in a congress populated by people who couldnt 
run again 
its a case neither side can prove in advance 
both sides agree that a constitutional amendment limiting terms 
would lead to more competitive congressional elections because it 
would force out incumbents and give newcomers a chance 
they also agree that it is not going to happen any time soon 
this is obviously going to come from outside the beltway 
quayle said the other day at a conference sponsored by the american 
enterprise institute it is not going to come through members 
of congress seeing the light all of a sudden 
he said it wasnt a partisan matter but term limits would do a 
lot more for the republican than for the democrats who have held 
control of the house for 36 years and have just extended it to 38 
forced retirements would open house seats and enhance gop chances 
in future congressional elections 
a term limit amendment was proposed in the last congress and 
will be introduced again next year but it wont get anywhere 
approval would take twothirds votes in each house advocates could 
get only 15 senators to sign on last time and two of them have 
since limited their own terms by retiring 
so the strategy of americans to limit congressional terms 
seeking to capitalize on the limits approved in three states this 
year is to build pressure for national limits by trying to get the 
voters to impose them on state legislatures 
they hope to get term limit measures on the ballots of at least 
15 states in the 1992 elections 
the group which calls itself a grassroots movement with more 
than 70000 members nationwide held its own conference this week 
to push its issue and plan the next campaign 
but first some of the limitation measures imposed this year 
will face challenges in the courts thats a sure thing in the case 
of the colorado limits which reach beyond state legislators and 
officeholders to cover senators and house members as well 
there also have been threats of court action against the state 
measure imposed in california and the city limits voted in kansas 
city 
president bush has endorsed congressional term limits but he 
hasnt pushed the issue quayle has as vice president and when he 
was in congress learned firsthand he says about the abuses that 
can go with seniority 
the longer one is in congress the more staff the more 
subcommittees you acquire and the more bureaucratic the government 
becomes quayle said 
critics countered that congressional newcomers lean more heavily 
on their staffs and are more susceptible to special interest 
influences 
well who do you think has the power right now quayle 
countered the special interest crowd likes the current 
system its comfortable they know the people 
he said the turnover produced by limiting terms would attract 
talent to congress lead people to vote with an eye on issues 
rather than on reelection and campaign fundraising strengthen 
party discipline encourage competition for committee 
chairmanships 
point by point critical questioners told him the result could 
as easily be the reverse arguing that those objectives can better 
be attained with election reform that would limit spending staffs 
free mailings and other advantages that make incumbents almost 
impossible to dislodge 
quayle said he doesnt look for real reform because incumbents 
would have to approve it adding that the prospect of term limits 
might give reformers the leverage to force action 
there is a voter revolt brewing he said 
 
editors note walter r mears vice president and columnist 
for the associated press has reported on washington and national 
politics for more than 25 years 
