<TEXT>
a controversial campaign urging 
citizens to avoid luxury goods has helped create south koreas 
worst trade frictions since seoul joined the ranks of the worlds 
top economies 
at stake are millions of dollars worth of services consumer 
goods and products from europe the united states and other nations 
that koreas most important trading partners claim have been 
blocked in the korean market 
foreign diplomats said that in the last year imports have been 
removed from stores consumers buying large items such as 
automobiles have been threatened with tax audits and some goods are 
being held at customs under obscure regulations 
goods as diverse as candycoated chocolates and luxury 
automobiles have been caught in the crossfire 
us ambassador donald p gregg said recently that rising trade 
friction threatens to undermine political and economic relations 
between washington and seoul the united states is south koreas 
largest trading partner and has been its chief ally for more than 
four deacades 
we dont like it particularly coming from korea us 
senator frank murkowski of alaska a frequent visitor to korea 
said he said there is a growing concern and support for the 
merits of retaliation 
korean officials maintain that the campaign is an earnest desire 
by citizens to restore frugality and austerity in koreas fast 
changing society government officials say they are hard put to 
stop it 
officials say the movement was not designed as a policy to 
discriminate against imports but they admit privately that in 
implementation some imports and koreas image as a fair trader have 
been hurt 
im not going to deny there was some misinterpretation said 
kim samhoon directorgeneral of the international trade bureau 
for the foreign ministry but we have many people who are 
spending excessively and wastefully 
the campaign is rife with cultural overtones western 
materialism and the right to sell to consumers vs a tightly knit 
homogeneous culture where conspicuous consumption is seen as moral 
decay 
the movement has been described as an antiimport campaign a 
consumers crusade an austerity campaign or a spiritual effort to 
restore basic confucian thrift 
western trading nations see the campaign as an antiimport 
drive secretly backed by the government and aimed at restricting 
access to foreign goods and services luxury koreanmade goods have 
not been targeted 
the american chamber of commerce which said the movement was 
targeted at imports was attacked by a band of radical students and 
remains under guard by plainclothes riot police 
the chamber said the campaign effectively reinstated a number 
of barriers to the importation of consumer goods and equated 
imported consumer goods with luxury goods it said korean 
consumers would benefit from more choices 
at no time did we challenge other aspects of the campaign 
frugality austerity cultural values confucian ethics a letter 
to chamber members said 
koreans feel foreigners do not appreciate the campaign as an 
extension of koreas confucian culture stressing fruguality and 
moderation they are offended by consumptionoriented western 
societies they feel destroy harmony by allowing the rich to be 
different 
the driving force behind this campaign is social discontent 
over the extravagant consumption of the rich deputy prime 
minister lee seungyun said 
he said misunderstandings have evolved because the campaign 
discourages buying unnecessary imports the reasonable 
consumption of foreign goods with regard to quality and price 
should not be criticized he said 
