<TEXT>
in a key case in the nations biggest worker 
health saga eaglepicher industries inc wants to provide up to 
80 million over 20 years to compensate asbestos disease victims 
and avoid declaring bankruptcy 
eaglepicher is widely viewed as a test case for dozens of 
companies saddled with huge liabilities stemming from the 
production and use of asbestos the insulation material that causes 
lung cancer and other respiratory diseases 
two attorneys representing asbestos plaintiffs wednesday 
proposed creating a trust that would begin making payments in 
november 1993 the trust would be funded with annual cash payments 
by eaglepicher and company stock 
under the plan eaglepicher would pay 460 million into the 
trust over 20 years 45 million for claims already negotiated and 
an estimated 178 million in proceeds from cash flow in company 
operations 
the attorneys said eaglepicher a cincinnatibased industrial 
and auto parts manufacturer needs to resolve the fate of more than 
65000 asbestos claims quickly or face a financial crisis and 
possible chapter 11 filing 
eaglepicher appears to be on the brink of bankruptcy unless 
its asbestosrelated liabilities are promptly settled attorneys 
stanley chesley and david i shapiro wrote in a 22page 
recommendation to us district judge jack b weinstein 
the evidence we have seen indicates that eaglepicher cannot 
generate enough cash from operations to pay its obligations as they 
mature the lawyers wrote 
but two other attorneys appointed by weinstein to negotiate with 
eaglepicher are opposing the plan saying it provides too little 
money to resolve existing claims and untold thousands of future 
claims 
the obligations of the company are minimal in relation to the 
number of persons who have sustained serious injury by way of 
occupational exposure to its products plaintiffs lawyer peter 
angelos of baltimore said 
a hearing was scheduled for friday on eaglepichers request 
that weinstein declare a classaction to resolve the claims on 
grounds the company cannot meet its asbestos liabilities 
a similar request has been made by the manville trust fund the 
nations largest asbestos resolution facility which faces about 
130000 claims but has run out of cash to pay new claims a 
proposal to restructure the trust is pending 
dozens of other former asbestos makers are watching the cases 
closely and judges nationwide are hopeful for model plan to clear 
a backlog of 90000 cases in state and federal courts payments to 
victims in some instances have been delayed for years and many 
workers have died before receiving compensation 
weinstein and asbestos defendants support converting companys 
claims into single class actions to reduce legal fees they say are 
exhausting assets that could be used to compensate victims 
eaglepicher has paid about 540 million in asbestos claims in 
the last five years court documents said the company no longer can 
sell assets issue common stock and debt or use tax refunds and 
insurance claims to meet its liabilities 
under the settlement plan eaglepicher would create an 
independent trust to resolve claims the company would contribute 
30 million in the first year 20 million per year for the next 
nine years and 25 million per year in the following 10 years for 
a total of 460 million 
in addition the trust after five years would receive 25 percent 
of eaglepicher common stock if the companys meets the payment 
plan and 50 percent if it does not 
eaglepicher would set aside 675 percent of its net sales each 
year to provide for basic operations the companys remaining cash 
flow would be split with the trust for a estimated 178 million 
about 45 million in claims already settled but held up by 
weinstein would be paid within 18 months 
shapiro and chesley said in the court papers that victims stand 
to receive more money faster if the company remains an operating 
entity than if it is forced seeks bankruptcy court protection 
eaglepichers claims stem from worker exposure to an 
asbestosbased pipe sealant the company made primarily for us 
government ships from 1934 to 1971 
