international publishing developments said these efforts hinge 
on hope that changes in the soviet economic system will open the 
country to western products and ideas 
in the meantime publishing ventures face nothing but problems 
in the short term in getting into the soviet union 
paper is in short supply printing operations are not up to 
western standards distribution systems are questionable the 
soviet ruble can not yet be converted into other currencies 
but melvin said the soviet union is proving a powerful lure to 
publishers with its 300 million consumers who have been 
economically isolated for years 
they have a great desire for the printed word virtually every 
magazine that is printed is gobbled up melvin said 
publishers who get in now will be ready to give advertisers a 
way to reach those readers once their products become available 
there he said 
