<TEXT>
the new zealand government said 
thursday it will allow foreign companies to increase their stake in 
radio and television companies 
communications minister maurice williamson said legislation 
providing for up to 499 percent shareholding by foreign companies 
in new zealand broadcasters will be introduced to parliament before 
the end of the month 
the current ratios are a maximum of 15 percent foreign ownership 
in television and up to 25 percent for radio 
the main beneficiary of the move is expected to be the 
financially troubled private tv3 network now operating in 
receivership 
the network launched just over a year ago as the first private 
competition to the two stations run by stateowned television new 
zealand attracts an average 15 percent viewing audience 
the national broadcasting co of the united states owns 75 
percent of tv3 after reducing its stake from 15 per cent 
tv3 reported a 28 million million loss for the year ending 
march 31 
williamson told a news conference that tv3s current financial 
predicament had given urgency to the matter 
williamson said consideration had been given to a 20 percent 
ratio as in australia or the united states figure of 25 percent 
but neither would have been satisfactory 
the existing overseas investment restrictions are now a 
serious impediment to the development of the broadcasting industry 
most large new zealand companies and institutions have significant 
overseas shareholding and it is proving impossible for such 
companies to have a worthwhile shareholding in broadcasting 
enterprises he said 
the 499 percent figure will allow new zealand broadcasters to 
seek equity partners overseas and along with the equity they will 
be able to seek expertise which is probably just as important 
he said 
