<TEXT>
an ambitious program of world trade 
talks was rescued from the brink of collapse today after the 
european community showed a willingness to discuss greater cuts in 
farm subsidies 
officials attending the uruguay round of negotiations decided to 
continue their talks rather than suspending them immediately 
because of a bitter dispute between the community and the united 
states over the subsidies 
the meeting decided we should go to work that we should 
continue the negotiations frans andriessen the communitys top 
trade official said after an hourlong session of negotiators 
he said the 12nation trading bloc made some movement and it 
was sufficient for the bargaining to continue 
the talks appeared near collapse earlier in the day because of 
the deadlock between the united states and european nations over 
farm issues 
i definitely think a coolingoff period might help the 
european community achieve a mandate us trade representative 
carla hills said after a round of morning sessions 
there was a stalemate in agricultural issues she said and it 
would be very constructive if we had a quiet period 
but the europeans promised to show new flexibility and rejected 
the drift toward suspending the current uruguay round of world 
trade talks 
while details on the europeans new offer were sketchy it 
appeared they were offering to discuss a us demand for 
acrosstheboard reductions in subsidies 
the impasse was broken said david woods spokesman for the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade the organization conducting 
the negotiations 
canadian trade minister john crosbie who earlier in the day had 
said chances for successfully concluding the talks appeared all but 
doomed said its not a breakthrough its a reprieve 
canada is a member of the cairns group of 14 major exporting 
countries who along with the united states have been pushing the 
europeans to agree to major cuts in subsidies 
australian trade minister neal blewett said the european 
proposal offered a glimmer of hope things are no longer 
terminal 
the announcement that after four days of stalemate the talks had 
gained new life came suddenly following a closeddoor session of 
the trade negotiators held to determine whether there was any use 
of proceeding further 
the europeans have offered to cut 30 percent from subsidies on 
major crops over 10 years starting retroactively in 1986 in order 
to reduce their farmers advantage over foreign producers and make 
imports more competitive 
the united states demand is for subsidy cuts of 75 percent to 
90 percent over the next decade 
at stake in the talks convened by the 107nation conference of 
the general agreement on tariffs and trade or gatt are more 
access to world markets for poor and newly democratizing countries 
protection against copyright theft and extension of fairtrade 
rulesto agriculture banking and textiles 
by washingtons calculation agreement could lead to a doubling 
of world trade by the end of the decade trade now amounts to 38 
trillion annually 
but in the corridors of the heysel palaces where the talks are 
being held delegates argued fiercely late wednesday over who was 
responsible for the slide toward a collapse or suspension of gatt 
more than 1500 delegates many of them cabinet members 
including four from washington attended the conference that 
started monday and was to end friday 
the talks are named the uruguay round after the country where 
they started in 1986 with the goal of liberalizing trade in 15 
areas 
backed by agriculturedependent countries in the third world 
the united states canada argentina brazil australia and others 
want the ec to make deep cuts in subsidies that have made the ecs 
10 million farmers into potent exporters the subsidies distort 
world farm trade reformers argue 
gatt was established in 1947 as a forum for promoting free 
trade the current round of talks the eighth since world war ii 
aims to extend free trade rules to areas not under current gatt 
rules such as farm products textiles and services such as 
financial services and construction 
