<TEXT>
a new soviet stock exchange founded with the help 
of the russian republic hopes to start trading bonds in january 
russian finance minister boris fyodorov said thursday 
the moscow international stock exchange is separate from a 
larger stock exchange founded in november the two possibly 
competing exchanges are the first to operate in the soviet union 
since dictator josef stalin banned them in the 1920s 
the reformminded russian government was joined by 19 other 
organizations and individuals to found the newest exchange last 
month fyodorov told a seminar on economic reforms in russia the 
largest and richest soviet republic 
the exchange will start with bonds and later will begin trading 
shares fyodorov said 
we would like to take in the first place a very primitive 
step fyodorov said we hope that the first session will be in 
the beginning of january with the state bonds 
many western experts advising the soviet union on how to revive 
and operate stock exchanges have recommended they start with bonds 
rather than equities to give the national and republic governments 
time to privatize factories and other means of production 
bonds issued by governments and corporations are considered 
less risky than stocks because they pay the buyer a fixed interest 
rate and can be redeemed at a specified future date 
david darbyshire a partner in arthur andersen the 
international services company that sponsored the seminar said 
bonds are also easy to understand 
he said the fledgling soviet markets need some early successes 
to encourage confidence and investor interest 
in the early stages of the exchange it will be critical that 
only those companies which have a fair chance of success should be 
allowed onto the marketplace he said 
among those most frequently mentioned are the state airline 
aeroflot the intourist travel agency and the oil and gas 
industries 
trading in stocks and bonds was outlawed following the 1917 
bolshevik revolution forcing the closure of an active 
200yearold exchange in st petersburg a moscow stock exchange 
and commodity exchanges were allowed a brief revival during the 
1920s before being abolished 
in october president mikhail s gorbachev issued sweeping 
decrees restoring soviets rights to buy stocks bonds and other 
securities 
the moscow stock exchange was founded in november by 187 
independent companies and without any government body that 
exchange said it would hold a trial bidding session in the spring 
it has has 615 million rubles or 341 million in capital 
by comparison fyodorov said the moscow international stock 
exchange has 10 million rubles or about 55 million in capital 
russias role in forming the moscow international stock exchange 
appeared to reflect the divergent economic agendas of the 
independentminded republics 
latvia on thursday passed its own law legalizing shareholder 
societies something other republics also have done latvian 
lawmakers warned investors to adhere to latvian rather than 
soviet law according to the independent news agency interfax 
meanwhile the new moscow commodity exchange said this week it 
has hired an american grain expert to develop its grain and 
agricultural commodities section 
it said myron laserson former president of the north american 
export grain association will head a sovietamerican team to 
develop and implement an efficient trading mechanism 
a russian commodity exchange begn trading in moscow this week 
and plans are in the works for both stock and commodity exchanges 
in leningrad 
