<DOCNO> AP901206-0229 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
trading in crude oil futures would be 
temporarily suspended in response to large price swings under a 
plan approved thursday by the new york mercantile exchange 
the plan to be considered by federal regulators would also 
limit the amount oil could rise or fall each day to 15 per barrel 
and the amount gasoline or home heating oil could rise or fall to 
40 cents a gallon each day 
exchange officials told a news conference that the plan was 
developed to ensure orderly trading in volatile situations such as 
a war in the persian gulf which could push prices higher or a 
sudden outbreak of peace which could send prices into a steep 
decline 
the officials denied bowing to any pressure from regulators or 
criticism that speculators were profiteering from wide swings in 
the futures market 
we were not goaded into this by any federal agency said 
merc chairman z lou guttman said we felt that this was a very 
responsible and necessary precautionary measure 
but oil market traders said the plan was aimed at heading off 
tighter regulation by the commodity futures trading commission 
rather than have the cftc close the exchange during war we 
could claim there are circuitbreakers said christian gohler a 
broker at merrill lynch energy futures thats the only redeeming 
quality 
david geary a cftc spokesman said the commission had not yet 
received the complete proposal from the exchange but he said the 
matter would be considered quickly exchange officials said they 
expected the plan to be approved by next wednesday 
a prominent critic of oil pricing sen joseph i lieberman 
dconn said the exchanges plan was a small step in the right 
direction but he said he would favor a government shutdown of the 
oil market if war broke out 
a 15abarrel increase in one day is still huge and 
unacceptable lieberman said in a telephone interview but 
lieberman praised the exchange officials for acknowledging they 
have some obligation to try to limit the increases in the price of 
oil due to panic 
oil traders pointed out that any limits at the exchange would 
not stop a big move by crude because there are no limits at the 
futures markets in london and singapore or in the spot market where 
buyers pay cash for oil at loading docks 
many doubt the exchanges limits would ever come into play 
because they are so wide 
its going to be in effect limitless trading which is the way 
the free markets are supposed to operate said brian tagler an 
oil broker at shearson lehman brothers inc 
the largest oneday move oil futures have made in new york 
occurred on oct 22 when crude dropped 541 per barrel largely 
in response to a rumor that iraqi president saddam hussein had a 
dream in which a prophet told him his missiles were pointed the 
wrong way the oil market took that to be a sign of peace in the 
middle east 
exchange officials said they were not trying to predict oil 
prices would move 15 daily after a war broke out they said the 
figure set conservative limits for the normal functioning of the 
market beyond those limits market participants might be unable to 
meet their obligations as buyers and sellers 
under the new rules if oil prices swing 750 in either 
direction during a single trading session and stay at that level 
for five minutes oil brokers would be told that trading would be 
halted in two minutes after a trading halt of one hour trading 
would resume with the swing in prices limited to another 750 for 
a total of 15 the limits would affect contracts for the two 
nearest delivery months 
trading of unleaded gasoline and home heating oil futures would 
follow a similar pattern with a maximum move of 40 cents a gallon 
in either direction on the two nearest months 
the exchange currently has no limits on moves made by contracts 
for nextmonth delivery of oil although there are limits on outer 
months 
exchange officials said the hours break in trading would give 
futures players time to take a closer look at world events that are 
pushing the price of crude 
</TEXT>
