<DOCNO> AP901206-0242 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
talks among 107 nations trying to draft 
an ambitious global trade pact neared collapse thursday night after 
the european community rejected a lastminute compromise making 
significant cuts in farm subsidies 
trade ministers suggested the ecs action virtually dooms any 
chances for reaching a trade agreement this week in brussels 
however many said they will campaign friday for holding more 
discussions after a coolingoff period 
however such a strategy runs a high risk of failure given 
tight deadlines imposed by the us congress for approving any 
final outcome under socalled fasttrack authority 
the battle between the united states and its trade allies on one 
side and the 12nation european community on the other turned out 
to be the biggest stumbling block to getting an overall agreement 
in the trade talks 
in a lastditch attempt to rescue the negotiations swedish 
agriculture minister mats hellstrom chairman of the farm 
negotiating panel put forward a proposal that represented a 
compromise between the drastic cuts in farm subsidies being sought 
by the united states and the minimal offer of the ec which was 
trying to protect its 10 million mainly small farmers 
the talks known as the uruguay round for the country where they 
began in 1986 had stalled in what was to have been the final week 
of bargaining 
the talks are being held under the auspices of the general 
agreement on tariffs and trade also known as gatt 
hellstrom suggested acrosstheboard cuts of 30 percent in 
internal farm supports export subsidies and market barriers over a 
fiveyear period 
but the hellstrom proposal brought strong objections almost 
immediately from community officials 
other countries who objected the proposal were south korea and 
japan which would have been forced to open its closed rice market 
to foreign imports under the proposal 
you will find that among ministers opinion strays from 
monstrous proposal shocking paper twice what the community 
has agreed to said ec agricultural commissioner ray macsharry 
talking to reporters he refused to be specific about what other 
cuts the ec was willing to make 
us negotiators are pushing for cuts of 75 percent in internal 
price supports and market barriers and 90 percent reductions in 
export subsidies over a 10year period 
us trade representative carla hills suggested the united 
states would be willing to accept smaller percentage reductions as 
long as it obtained binding commitments from the ec to make 
reductions in all three areas 
the united states and some other major exporting countries 
including canada have been pushing the europeans to relent and 
agree to major cuts in subsidies 
without movement on agriculture it is likely the trade talks 
will be suspended perhaps for up to a month 
neal blewett the australian trade minister said it is now time 
for the countries to turn their attention to trying to rescue the 
overall trade package by setting up a fallback meeting possibly 
in january 
the united states had insisted such a strategy was risky given 
a march 1 deadline imposed by congress for submitting a complete 
deal and the necessary time to put the nearly 300page document in 
shape 
the reduction in farm subsidies is being pushed hard by the bush 
administration washington sees the change as a boost to american 
farm exports as well as those of many farmbased third world 
nations which cannot compete with the huge subisidies offered by 
the developed world 
more than 1500 delegates including four members of bushs 
cabinet have been taking part in the negotiations which began on 
monday and were scheduled to end on friday 
gatt was established in 1947 as a forum for promoting free 
trade the current round of talks is the eighth since world war ii 
</TEXT>
