<TEXT>
continental airlines officials made misleading 
comments about the troubled carriers plans to seek bankruptcy 
protection in an effort to prop up its stock value according to a 
lawsuit filed thursday 
former chairman frank lorenzo and others artificially inflated 
the market price of continental stock by denying in interviews with 
the news media that the nations fifthlargest airline was 
considering filing for bankruptcy protection according to the 
lawsuit filed on behalf of shareholders 
continental disputed the allegations 
as far as this airline is concerned that suit is utterly 
without merit spokesman art kent said from houston in no way 
were our shareholders or the public misled by any statements that 
were made at the time those statements were made we had no intent 
to file for protection under chapter 11 
continental filed for chapter 11 protection from creditors on 
monday saying it was forced into bankruptcy court by soaring fuel 
costs and mounting interest payments on its 62 billion debt 
the shareholders lawsuit a class action filed in us district 
court was brought on behalf of investors who purchased continental 
stock between oct 24 and the airlines bankruptcy filing 
the shareholders said that during this time period airline 
officials publicly denied their intention to seek bankruptcy 
protection even though such action was continually under 
consideration as a solution to continentals worsening liquidity 
and other financial problems 
the lawsuit accuses the airline officials of violating 
securities laws and seeks unspecified damages because of losses on 
investments 
according to the lawsuit continental stock fell from 362 per 
share to 2 per share after the bankruptcy filing 
in addition to lorenzo the lawsuit names jan carlzon chairman 
of scandinavian airlines system continentals largest shareholder 
continental chairman carl r pohlad and hollis harris president 
and chief executive officer of continental 
</TEXT>
