<TEXT>
faced with rising local wages and 
other problems foreign corporate investors withdrew 110 million 
from south korea in the first nine months of 1990 the finance 
ministry said friday 
approvals on new foreign capital investment in south korea from 
january to september totaled 632 million down 269 percent from 
the same period last year ministry officials said 
the total amount of foreign capital investment remaining in 
south korea was listed at 566 billion at the end of september 
withdrawals of direct foreign investment from the country 
totaled 75 million in 1989 and 48 million in 1988 it was not 
known how many foreign businesses were involved in the capital 
withdrawals in the past three years 
the declines were attributed to worsening investment conditions 
such as steep local wage hikes labor unrest and a slowdown in 
local economic growth 
even many korean businesses in recent years have relocated 
manufacturing and other operations to other countries where labor 
is available at lower cost without unrest 
