<TEXT>
wheelingpittsburgh steel corp on thursday 
asked a federal judge to confirm a reorganization plan to keep the 
company in business by giving 600 million in cash to creditors 
executives of the nations 10thlargest steelmaker said at a 
hearing before us bankruptcy judge warren bentz the plan will 
allow the company the remain competitive with other steel 
companies 
under the proposed reorganization unsecured creditors would be 
paid 72 cents per 1 of debt 
the remaining challenger to the plan is a joint interest of the 
us farmers home administration and equibank which is owed 44 
million 
bentz on thursday dismissed a claim by the us environmental 
protection agency which sought to force wheelingpittsburgh to 
place pollutioncontrol devices on its mills 
the agency wanted wheelingpittsburgh to place cash in an escrow 
account for the machinery but bentz said the agency would have to 
sue in another court for such an order 
the plan before the judge would create two corporations a 
holding company wheelingpittsburgh corp chaired by new york 
investor ronald lebow who purchased 86 percent of secured debt 
and an operating company wheelingpittsburgh steel corp 
liquidating the companys assets would be unsound said james t 
gibbons wheeling pittsburghs director of reorganization and 
planning 
gibbons estimated the value of a liquidated wheelingpittsburgh 
at 860 million to 870 million in contrast the reorganized 
company would be worth at least 11 billion he said 
gibbons told bentz that wheelingpittsburgh is a leaner more 
competitive company than the one that filed for protection from its 
creditors in 1985 
a major step toward recovery was the closing of the monessen 
steel mill which was operating at 30 percent capacity gibbons 
said the mill was sold in 1988 to other steel makers 
wheelingpittsburgh employs 7100 people in ohio west virginia 
and pennsylvania 
</TEXT>
